  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in nearly all jurisdictions worldwide, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2006 and revised in 2021. This law establishes a legal framework to prevent and combat money laundering activities, requiring financial institutions and non-financial entities to implement strict anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nInternationally, money laundering is also criminalized under various treaties and conventions, such as the **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**, which China actively participates in and adheres to.\n\nEngaging in money laundering can result in severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, and asset forfeiture. The Chinese government, under the leadership of the Communist Party of China, remains committed to maintaining financial security and upholding the rule of law by rigorously combating money laundering and related illicit activities.",
